{"id":"2108.10728","submitter":"Keehang Kwon","authors":"Keehang Kwon","title":"What is an Algorithm?: a Modern View","comments":"6 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.LO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Although algorithm is one of the central subjects, there have been little\ncommon understandings of what an algorithm is. For example, Gurevich view\nalgorithms as abstract state machines, while others view algorithms as\nrecursors. We promote a third view: it is a combination to these two disparate\nviews. This approach -- based on computability logic -- describes an algorithm\nas $A(I,O)$ where $I$ is a set of input services and $O$ an output service. It\nleads to the following modern definition: {\\it An algorithm $A$ is a (tree of)\nsequence of legal moves for providing $O$ using $I$. } In the above, $A$ is\nwritten in an imperative language/abstract state machine and $I,O$ are written\nin recursors/logical specifications.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 18 Aug 2021 09:09:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-25"}
